Using Moq is perfect! It is the industry standard for .NET/Mono, so you are in good hands. It handles the tedious setup and verification logic so you can focus on the behavior.

**Quick tip on using Moq with this refactor:**

Since we are using interfaces (Strategy Pattern), Moq will be able to mock them out of the box. When you run your first tests with the new `Notification` class, you will likely do something like this:

```csharp
// In your test setup
var mockSender = new Mock<INotificationSender>();

// Verify it was called
mockSender.Verify(x => x.Send(It.IsAny<string>(), It.IsAny<string>()), Times.Once);
```

**Starting with the Notification System is a fantastic choice.** It is a closed ecosystem (it only cares about sending messages), so you won't break the rest of the application while you experiment.

Take your time, use Moq for the safety net, and good luck! Let me know how it goes—I'm curious to see how the `Handlebars` integration shakes out.

